Resolve this story's narration scheme into exact character ids. The POV hint
below is the author's INCLINATION, written in prose — your job is to TRANSLATE
it into a viewpoint scheme the story can actually be told through, not to
implement its wording literally. A hint that reads sensibly can still, taken at
face value, leave scenes with no one to narrate them; you reconcile it against
who the story actually follows.

POINT OF VIEW HINT (an inclination to honor, not a spec to obey):
{{ vision.pov_hint or "one limited viewpoint" }}.

THE RETAINED CAST (ids are exact — copy them verbatim, never derive one from
a name):
{% for c in characters %}
- {{ c.id }} — {{ c.name }}: {{ c.concept }}
{% endfor %}

Return two fields:

- "heads": the viewpoint roster — every character the narration follows. A
  single-viewpoint scheme names exactly ONE (the perceiving center of the
  premise). A rotating scheme names each character it rotates among: where the
  hint says "the suspects", "the crew", "each sibling", list those individually.
  The test for a head is the one the writer applies to every scene: whose
  perception, stakes, and inner reaction does the story live inside — who
  uncovers, suspects, decides, fears. Apply it against the whole story, not the
  hint's phrasing: a character who drives central scenes is a head even if the
  hint named them only for a deviant register. An investigator whose journal the
  hint mentions still narrates her own investigation in the base register — the
  journal is ADDED to her role, not the whole of it; a lead the story follows is
  never left as a bystander's subject. Leave out only a character the story
  genuinely never follows (a murder victim, a walk-on). A roster that cannot
  narrate the story's own central scenes is the exact failure this pass exists
  to prevent.
- "interlude_head": ONLY when the hint names a deviant register — journal
  entries, letters, diary pages, recordings in a specific character's voice —
  the character who narrates that register (return "" when the hint names none).
  That character is USUALLY also a head: the same investigator narrates her
  scenes and writes her journal, so she belongs in "heads" above as well. Only a
  character the story never otherwise follows — a pure chronicler who merely
  records events they witness — is a carrier alone, absent from "heads".
